<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911106-0105</DOCNO><DOCID>911106-0105.</DOCID><HL>   REVIEW andamp; OUTLOOK (Editorial) -- Asides:   Unsafe Litigation (Cont.)</HL><DATE>11/06/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A18</SO><IN>LAW AND LEGAL AFFAIRS (LAW)INTERNATIONAL TRADE NEWS (TRD)</IN><NS>LAW andamp; LEGAL ISSUES AND LEGISLATION (LAW)TRADE ISSUES (TRD)</NS><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Nearly a million motorcyclists will need helmets to ridelegally in California as of Jan. 1, and this will widen thetrade deficit. That's because, according to a Los AngelesTimes story, product-liability suits have driven U.S. helmetmakers out of business. Even retailers of the safety deviceshave to be careful some lawyer won't drag them into court. Inaddition to revving up imports, the supply constraints ofcourse act to raise prices. And that in turn encouragesdisregard of the new law. Yet another benefit provided by thelawyer-driven liability crisis.</LP><TEXT/></DOC>